{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17637004","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17637004"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:36:33+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:36:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17620"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17620","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17620"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10334"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71666"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10334","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10334"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17620"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57162"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4948"},{"type":"tags","id":"7717"},{"type":"tags","id":"7748"},{"type":"tags","id":"7750"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24177"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24185"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71666","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/71666"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA researcher measures the serum calcium concentration in 100 healthy adults and calculates a sample mean of 2.4 mmol/L with a standard deviation of 0.1 mmol/L. The 95% confidence interval is calculated as 2.38 to 2.42 mmol/L.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following would most likely decrease the width of this confidence interval?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Decreasing the sample size to 50","Increasing the confidence level to 99%","Increasing the sample size to 400","Using a two-tailed rather than one-tailed test","Increasing the standard deviation to 0.2 mmol/L"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe width of a confidence interval is determined by the formula: width = 2 \u00d7 (critical value \u00d7 standard error), where standard error = standard deviation/\u221an.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreasing the sample size to 400\u003C/strong\u003E would decrease the standard error and therefore narrow the confidence interval width.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other options would either increase the interval width or have no effect:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreasing the sample size to 50\u003C/strong\u003E would increase the standard error and widen the interval\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreasing the confidence level to 99%\u003C/strong\u003E would require a larger critical value (2.576 instead of 1.96) and widen the interval\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUsing a two-tailed rather than one-tailed test\u003C/strong\u003E would not affect the confidence interval width\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreasing the standard deviation to 0.2 mmol/L\u003C/strong\u003E would increase the standard error and widen the interval\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe relationship between sample size and confidence interval width is inverse - as sample size increases, the width decreases, assuming all other factors remain constant.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["A confidence interval provides a range of plausible values for a population parameter with a specified level of confidence.","The width of a confidence interval depends on the sample size, standard deviation, and desired confidence level.","A 95% confidence interval means if we repeated the sampling process many times, 95% of intervals would contain the true population mean."],"references":["Sullivan LM. Essentials of biostatistics in public health. 3rd ed. Burlington (MA): Jones \u0026 Bartlett Learning; 2018.","Dawson B, Trapp RG. Basic \u0026 clinical biostatistics. 4th ed. New York: McGraw-Hill; 2004."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57162"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17620"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57162","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/57162"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-20T10:44:27+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-20T10:45:59+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10334"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71666"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4948","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4948"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udcca","name":"Biostatistics","synonyms":[],"descrip